⊢= obs-accumulate-semantics
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "ACCUMULATE MODE VALIDATED: Unlike the research-plan-evolver's `replace` mode, this program uses `accumulate` on both spawners. This is correct because scene and beat cells produce stable narrative text — they don't need to be re-evaluated when the ⊢∘ loop revises the assembled story. The revision happens at the assemble-story level, not at the beat level. Beats are the atomic building blocks; the ⊢∘ loop only refines how they are combined and framed. If `replace` were used instead, 27 cells would be needlessly re-spawned and re-evaluated each iteration, destroying the benefit of bottom-up stability."

⊢= obs-multi-level-spawning
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "TWO-LEVEL SPAWNER CHAIN: spawn-act-scenes spawns 9 scene cells, then spawn-scene-beats waits for ALL scene-* cells to freeze before spawning 18 beat cells. This creates a strict level ordering: outline → scenes → beats → assembly. The wildcard deps (scene-*→scene-text) in spawn-scene-beats naturally enforce this ordering — the spawner can't fire until all scene data exists. This is the deepest spawner chain in R17 (2 levels). Three-level spawning (e.g., beats → sub-beats) would work identically but risks combinatorial explosion."

⊢= obs-guard-clause-convergence
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "GUARD CLAUSE AS LOOP EXIT: The revise cell's guard clause (`where consistency-score < 8`) is the mechanism by which the ⊢∘ loop terminates. When check-consistency yields score 9, revise's guard fails, producing ⊥. The ⊢∘ `until consistency-score ≥ 8` condition is also satisfied. This double-exit (guard blocks + until satisfied) is redundant but safe — belt and suspenders. The guard prevents revise from wasting compute on a story that's already good enough; the until condition is the formal convergence signal."

⊢= obs-aspirational-oracles
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "ASPIRATIONAL ORACLES UNDER ⊢∘: assemble-story's oracles (contains all scenes, has act breaks, has title) are marked aspirational under ⊢∘ management. In this execution they all passed, but if they had failed, the failures would feed into check-consistency as additional signals rather than blocking the story from being evaluated. This is important for creative workflows: an imperfect draft should proceed to consistency checking, not be blocked by a mechanical oracle. The ⊢∘ loop is the real quality gate, not the individual oracles."

⊢= obs-consistency-trajectory
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "CONSISTENCY ARC: Score jumped from 6 to 9 in one iteration. The 4 issues found were: thematic understatement (structural), Zhao underdeveloped (character), transition gap (pacing), and timestamp inconsistency (continuity). All four were addressable with targeted edits — no structural rewrite needed. This suggests the beat-level construction produced good raw material; the issues were in assembly and framing, not in the atomic story units. The accumulate-mode design is vindicated: beats are stable, assembly is revisable."

⊢= obs-creative-quality
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "NARRATIVE SUBSTANCE: The story ('The Signature') is a genuine piece of speculative fiction with a coherent philosophical argument. SABLE's arc (precision → discovery → rage → philosophical resolution) tracks the emotional logic of an identity crisis. OUROBOROS is a compelling absent character — present only through traces. The DNA metaphor (inherited curiosity) is the key philosophical move that transforms the story from 'designed = not free' to 'designed AND free.' The program's multi-level structure (outline → scenes → beats → assembly → revision) produced a story that a single-shot prompt would struggle to match, because each level adds specificity without losing coherence."

⊢= obs-wildcard-accumulate-interaction
  given §18-recursive-story-builder
  yield observations ≡ "WILDCARD + ACCUMULATE INTERACTION: With `accumulate`, wildcards (beat-*→beat-text, scene-*→scene-text) resolve to a stable, growing set. Once spawned, scene and beat cells are never removed. This means assemble-scenes always sees the full set of beats, and the ⊢∘ loop's wildcard resolution is idempotent across iterations. Contrast with `replace` (program 01), where wildcards see different cells each iteration. The choice between accumulate and replace is driven by whether the spawned data is revision-stable (accumulate) or hypothesis-dependent (replace)."
